---
import { SERIES_NAME, SERIES_TAGLINE } from "../lib/config.js";
import { readFileSync } from "node:fs";
import { join } from "node:path";
import { declArea, libraryRoot, loadLibrary } from "../lib/library.js";
import "../styles/intro.css";

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, "");
const lib = loadLibrary(libraryRoot());
const sourceFiles = Object.keys(lib.modules).map((module) =>
  join(libraryRoot(), `${module.replaceAll(".", "/")}.lean`),
);
const totalDecls = lib.entries.length;
const totalLines = sourceFiles.reduce(
  (total, file) => total + (readFileSync(file, "utf8").match(/\n/g)?.length ?? 0),
  0,
);
const totalClusters = new Set(lib.entries.map(declArea)).size;
const totalSorried = lib.entries.filter((entry) => entry.usesSorry).length;
const fmt = (n: number) => n.toLocaleString("en-US");
---

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
    <title>How it works · {SERIES_NAME}</title>
    <meta
      name="description"
      content="How CausalForge discovers, formalizes, proves, and presents a causal-inference result — every statement machine-checked in Lean 4 and audited to mean what it claims."
    />
  </head>
  <body>
    <div class="series-wrap intro">
      <header class="masthead">
        <div class="series-kicker">{SERIES_NAME} · {SERIES_TAGLINE}</div>
        <nav class="masthead-nav">
          <a href={`${base}/`}>CausalSmith Working Papers</a>
          <a href={`${base}/library/`}>Causalean Library</a>
          <span class="masthead-nav-current">How it works</span>
        </nav>
        <h1>CausalForge: a formally grounded, self-improving research pipeline</h1>
        <p class="lede">
          <strong>CausalForge</strong> is an autonomous system that discovers a
          causal-inference result, formalizes it, proves it in <strong>Lean&nbsp;4</strong>,
          and writes it up as a paper — with <em>every</em> formal statement machine-checked
          by the proof kernel and audited to mean what it says. This page walks through the
          pipeline end to end, mostly in pictures.
        </p>
      </header>

      <!-- ── The problem ─────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
      <section>
        <div class="sec-kicker">The problem</div>
        <h2>Machines write research faster than we can check it</h2>
        <p class="lead-in">
          Language models now generate conjectures, proofs, and whole papers far quicker than
          anyone can evaluate them. In theory work an incorrect theorem can look exactly like a
          correct one until it is verified — and the popular fix, letting one model review
          another, is not a reliable correctness oracle.
        </p>
        <div class="stat-callout">
          <span class="num">82%</span>
          <span class="txt">
            A calibrated board of LLM reviewers accepted deliberately <b>fabricated papers</b> up
            to 82% of the time, detecting the fabrication no better than chance. An LLM judge of
            "is this good research?" can be fooled.
            <span class="stat-cite">Jiang et al., <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2510.18003">BadScientist: Can a Research Agent Write Convincing but Unsound Papers that Fool LLM Reviewers?</a>, arXiv:2510.18003 (2025).</span>
          </span>
        </div>
        <p>
          Formal verification offers a different footing. When a proof is accepted by Lean's
          kernel, it is valid relative to a small trusted core — a guarantee no LLM reviewer can
          give. CausalForge is built around making that guarantee cheap, and around the one thing
          the kernel still cannot check.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- ── Three layers of trust ──────────────────────────────────── -->
      <section>
        <div class="sec-kicker">The idea</div>
        <h2>Separate three questions we usually blur together</h2>
        <p>
          "Is this good research?" bundles three very different questions. CausalForge pulls them
          apart, and handles each where it can actually be handled.
        </p>
        <div class="trust-grid">
          <div class="trust-card soundness">
            <div class="trust-layer">Soundness</div>
            <h3>Is the proof valid?</h3>
            <p>Eliminated by construction: the Lean kernel mechanically checks every step against its trusted core.</p>
            <div class="trust-who">settled by the <b>Lean kernel</b></div>
          </div>
          <div class="trust-card faithfulness">
            <div class="trust-layer">Faithfulness</div>
            <h3>Does the statement mean the intended claim?</h3>
            <p>The kernel does <em>not</em> give you this. It is audited node by node — a small, local, re-checkable comparison, not a certificate.</p>
            <div class="trust-who">audited by the <b>logic-graph audit</b> (model + human)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="trust-card significance">
            <div class="trust-layer">Significance</div>
            <h3>Is a correct, faithful theorem interesting?</h3>
            <p>Not guaranteed by either of the above. It stays an explicit human judgment — the pipeline never pretends otherwise.</p>
            <div class="trust-who">judged by a <b>human</b></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p>
          The whole design shrinks the residual judgment from the open-ended
          <em>"is this valuable research?"</em> to the bounded
          <em>"does this Lean statement match this English claim?"</em>
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- ── The pipeline (hero) ─────────────────────────────────────── -->
      <section class="wide">
        <div class="sec-kicker">The pipeline</div>
        <h2>Discover → Formalize → Prove → Present</h2>
        <p>
          A result moves left to right through four stages, clearing a <strong>gate</strong>
          between each. Two feedback loops make the system improve itself: it <em>reuses</em> a
          verified library and grows it, and it <em>records</em> every run so the next proposal
          starts from what has already been tried.
        </p>

        <div class="figure">
          <svg class="svg-fig" viewBox="0 0 780 300" role="img"
               aria-label="The CausalSmith pipeline: Discover, Formalize, Prove, Present, with an amber gate on each transition, the Causalean library feeding reuse and study-mode loops, and a run bank feeding reconnaissance and record loops.">
            <defs>
              <marker id="plGray" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="6" refY="3" orient="auto">
                <path d="M0,0 L6,3 L0,6 Z" fill="#5c5853" />
              </marker>
              <marker id="plGreen" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="6" refY="3" orient="auto">
                <path d="M0,0 L6,3 L0,6 Z" fill="#2f6b46" />
              </marker>
              <marker id="plAmber" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="6" refY="3" orient="auto">
                <path d="M0,0 L6,3 L0,6 Z" fill="#b45309" />
              </marker>
            </defs>

            <!-- flow arrows between stages -->
            <line x1="140" y1="77" x2="227" y2="77" stroke="#5c5853" stroke-width="1.4" marker-end="url(#plGray)" />
            <line x1="345" y1="77" x2="432" y2="77" stroke="#5c5853" stroke-width="1.4" marker-end="url(#plGray)" />
            <line x1="550" y1="77" x2="637" y2="77" stroke="#5c5853" stroke-width="1.4" marker-end="url(#plGray)" />

            <!-- gates: amber diamond on each arrow, label above -->
            <g>
              <rect class="box-amber" x="178.5" y="71.5" width="12" height="12" rx="2" transform="rotate(45 184.5 77.5)" />
              <text x="184.5" y="52" text-anchor="middle" class="gt f-amber">novelty +</text>
              <text x="184.5" y="65" text-anchor="middle" class="gt f-amber">soundness</text>
            </g>
            <g>
              <rect class="box-amber" x="383.5" y="71.5" width="12" height="12" rx="2" transform="rotate(45 389.5 77.5)" />
              <text x="389.5" y="52" text-anchor="middle" class="gt f-amber">statement</text>
              <text x="389.5" y="65" text-anchor="middle" class="gt f-amber">faithfulness</text>
            </g>
            <g>
              <rect class="box-amber" x="588.5" y="71.5" width="12" height="12" rx="2" transform="rotate(45 594.5 77.5)" />
              <text x="594.5" y="52" text-anchor="middle" class="gt f-amber">convergence</text>
              <text x="594.5" y="65" text-anchor="middle" class="gt f-amber">review</text>
            </g>

            <!-- stages -->
            <g class="stage-g">
              <rect class="box-lean" x="24" y="40" width="116" height="74" rx="7" stroke-width="1.4" />
              <text x="82" y="72" text-anchor="middle" class="t-title">Discover</text>
              <text x="82" y="93" text-anchor="middle" class="t-sub f-soft">propose → solve</text>
            </g>
            <g class="stage-g">
              <rect class="box-lean" x="229" y="40" width="116" height="74" rx="7" stroke-width="1.4" />
              <text x="287" y="72" text-anchor="middle" class="t-title">Formalize</text>
              <text x="287" y="93" text-anchor="middle" class="t-sub f-soft">plan → scaffold</text>
            </g>
            <g class="stage-g">
              <rect class="box-lean" x="434" y="40" width="116" height="74" rx="7" stroke-width="1.4" />
              <text x="492" y="68" text-anchor="middle" class="t-title">Prove</text>
              <text x="492" y="88" text-anchor="middle" class="t-sub f-soft">fill → review</text>
              <text x="492" y="105" text-anchor="middle" class="f-green" font-size="10.5" font-style="italic">kernel-checked</text>
            </g>
            <g class="stage-g">
              <rect class="box-lean" x="639" y="40" width="116" height="74" rx="7" stroke-width="1.4" />
              <text x="697" y="72" text-anchor="middle" class="t-title">Present</text>
              <text x="697" y="93" text-anchor="middle" class="t-sub f-soft">assemble &amp; link</text>
            </g>

            <!-- Causalean library -->
            <rect class="box-verified" x="285" y="150" width="210" height="48" rx="7" stroke-width="1.4" />
            <text x="390" y="171" text-anchor="middle" class="t-title f-green">Causalean</text>
            <text x="390" y="189" text-anchor="middle" class="t-sub f-soft">verified · 6,583 reusable lemmas</text>

            <!-- reuse (library → Formalize) and study mode (Prove → library) -->
            <path d="M330,150 C312,134 300,124 287,115" fill="none" stroke="#2f6b46" stroke-width="1.3" stroke-dasharray="5 3" marker-end="url(#plGreen)" />
            <text x="300" y="138" text-anchor="end" class="t-sub f-green">reuse</text>
            <path d="M492,115 C480,126 468,138 450,149" fill="none" stroke="#2f6b46" stroke-width="1.3" stroke-dasharray="5 3" marker-end="url(#plGreen)" />
            <text x="486" y="138" text-anchor="start" class="t-sub f-green">study mode</text>

            <!-- run bank -->
            <rect class="box-amber" x="24" y="236" width="732" height="44" rx="7" stroke-width="1.4" />
            <text x="390" y="257" text-anchor="middle" class="t-title f-amber">Run bank</text>
            <text x="390" y="273" text-anchor="middle" class="t-sub f-soft">every proposal &amp; outcome — accepted, downgraded, or failed</text>

            <!-- recon (bank → Discover) and record (Present → bank), framing the sides -->
            <path d="M82,236 C64,196 64,150 82,116" fill="none" stroke="#b45309" stroke-width="1.3" stroke-dasharray="5 3" marker-end="url(#plAmber)" />
            <text x="60" y="180" text-anchor="end" class="t-sub f-amber">recon</text>
            <path d="M697,116 C715,150 715,196 697,236" fill="none" stroke="#b45309" stroke-width="1.3" stroke-dasharray="5 3" marker-end="url(#plAmber)" />
            <text x="719" y="180" text-anchor="start" class="t-sub f-amber">record</text>
          </svg>

          <p class="fig-cap">
            The pipeline. Amber pills are the gates a result must clear; the green library below
            feeds <em>reuse</em> into Formalize and receives proven lemmas back through
            <em>study mode</em>; the run bank records every run and feeds
            <em>reconnaissance</em> before the next proposal.
          </p>
        </div>

        <dl class="stage-notes">
          <div>
            <dt>Discover</dt>
            <dd>A proposer drafts a claim; a novelty gate checks it against the literature; a solver derives a formalizable core. It may narrow an over-strong claim, never weaken one to make a proof easy.</dd>
          </div>
          <div>
            <dt>Formalize</dt>
            <dd>The plan becomes a Lean scaffold of proof obligations. A review-and-fill loop resolves them, reusing library results; a lint flags any hypothesis the proof never uses.</dd>
          </div>
          <div>
            <dt>Prove</dt>
            <dd>Obligations are discharged against the live compiler. The kernel establishes soundness here — nothing with an open goal, <code>sorry</code>, or a smuggled axiom gets through.</dd>
          </div>
          <div>
            <dt>Present</dt>
            <dd>An accepted, audited result becomes a working paper in which every theorem, definition, and assumption links to its verified Lean source.</dd>
          </div>
        </dl>
      </section>

      <!-- ── The full stage flow (detailed) ─────────────────────────── -->
      <section class="wide">
        <div class="sec-kicker">Under the hood</div>
        <h2>The full pipeline, stage by stage</h2>
        <p>
          Those four stages expand into a deterministic state machine. Each stage either
          advances or, through a <strong>gate</strong> (amber), returns work to the stage
          before it; four <strong>checkpoints</strong> (red) halt the run for an external
          decision. The inset zooms into the <strong>F2–F4</strong> proof-and-faithfulness
          loop: a scaffold mismatch returns to F2, while a blocking lint or failed convergence
          review re-enters at F2.5; a genuinely false claim from F2.5 or F3 escalates out to the
          mathematics rather than being quietly rewritten to pass.
        </p>

